title.narrative: OUTPUT 2: INTEGRATED NEWBORN AND CHILD-HEALTH INTERVENTIONS

description.narrative: By 2022, children under 5 years, their mothers and adolescents in targeted districts and high-risk urban areas have access to integrated MNCAH and immunization services in emergency and non-emergency situations.,which contributes to Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, the most at-risk newborns and children are benefiting from integrated newborn, child health interventions and healthy behaviours.

description.narrative: UNICEF contributed to generating evidence to inform policy development, advocacy and implementation of equity-focused MNCH and immunization programmes. All four provinces of Pakistan have now developed and are implementing newborn survival strategies and costed action plans. Punjab developed a Health Sector Strategy to guide the government sector plan in health. Knowledge was generated through profiling of 4,147 urban slums, evaluating the Lady Health Worker (LHW) and PMTCT programmes. These are being used to develop policy briefs and advocate for new strategies on LHWs, newborn care and HIV response as well as to develop the Universal Health Coverage Benefit Package. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:10/01/2020
